text:
Sheriff Street, north from and including Grand Street, showing (right), the plants of R.Hoe & Co., extending to Delancey after crossing Broome Streets. (The plants are now, 1937, demolished). Also shown is a portion of the Williamsburg Bridge.

April 1, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.

Grand Street, north side, east from and including Sheriff, to and including Columbia Streets. Also shown is Sheriff Street, east side, north from and including Grand, to and including Delancey Streets. In the background on Delancey Street, is the Williamsburg Bridge.

About 1930.

Joseph P. Day.

Sheriff Street, west side, south from Delancey, to and including Grand Streets, showing P.S. No. 34 (prior to 1931), at the N.W. corner of Broome Street. This school bears No. 106 of the latter street. July 1, 1930.

P. L. Sperr.

Sheriff Street, east side, south from Delancey, to and including Grand Streets, showing a 5-story annex of the R. Roe & Co. printing press manufacturers, occupying the block from Delancey to Broome Streets. Shown, under demolition, is the main plant of the same concern extending from Broome to Grand Streets.
June 6, 1930
P. L. Sperr

title: Tenements and storefronts: Sheriff St. - Delancey St., Manhattan
Tenements & storefronts; H. Yager, carpenter: 61 Sheriff St-Delancey St., Manhattan
